[3] Response
- Fri 27 Sep 2019. Role of media
[Actualite, in French, Google trans., abridged, edited]
https://actualite.cd/2019/09/27/ebola-lapport-des-medias-aussi-permis-aux-communautes-du-nord-kivu-de-sapproprier-la

Ebola: Media input has also enabled communities in North Kivu to take ownership of the response to the epidemic

The number of new cases of the Ebola outbreak has dropped on the ground in North Kivu province. This is also thanks to the involvement of the media in raising awareness of the population on the danger of the disease. Indeed, since the appearance of the 10th epidemic in August 2018 in Beni, the response teams have mobilized the media to help educate communities on prevention measures.

A synergy of journalists has been created to produce programs and magazines focused on Ebola, in spite of the particular security, socioeconomic, and health contexts in which their media organizations operate.

"I feel comfortable when I take my camera, and I will do a report on Ebola. I feel like I'm helping to save a soul who was dying from this disease somewhere because of a lack of information," says Hope Channel TV journalist Yvonne Kapinga.

The president of the National Press Union of Congo (UNPC), North Kivu branch, Rosalie Zawadi says that the roles of the media have also helped prevent rumors of any kind about this deadly epidemic. "Rumors were too prevalent about this disease. Media professionals have helped to make it clear that Ebola is a fast-healed disease if we go to the ETC (Ebola treatment center) quickly, and the community quickly adopted the response," she says.

The interim governor of North Kivu, Jean-Bosco Sebishimbo, also acknowledges the contribution of the media to reduce community resistance to Ebola response teams. "It is through diversified broadcasts bringing everyone to subscribe to the program against Ebola that we continue to record satisfactory results," he says.

It is within this context that a collective of community radio and television stations of North Kivu (CORACON), which benefits from the support of the English organization Free Press unlimited, equipped the community media with working tools (computers, dictaphones) on Thursday [26 Sep 2019].

"We have provided each of our 33 radio partners with work tools for the production of awareness programs. Emissions that inform the public in real time about the right attitudes to take in the process of fighting Ebola virus disease, "says Innocent Pendakazi, chairman of the board of CORACON.

From the rostrum of the 74th UN General Assembly Thursday [26 Sep 2019], Congolese President Felix Tshisekedi has acknowledged a step forward in the fight against Ebola that has lasted more than a year.

"The new response strategy is starting to take effect, especially in the city of Goma, which is now immune to the virus. Although much has been done, the epidemic is not yet eradicated. The strategy will be strengthened by the introduction of 5 new approved drugs, in addition to the Ebola vaccine, which will completely eliminate this scourge," he said.

